# Deobfuscated Code

Here's the fully deobfuscated and readable version:

```javascript
// Constants
var TAU = 6.283;           // ~2π
var PHI = 1.618;           // Golden ratio
var SQRT_HALF = 0.707;     // ~√(1/2)

// Physics configuration
var config = {
  attraction: 4000,
  frictionCoeff: 0.004,
  amplification: 0.92,
  dispersal: 0.0003,
  streamMax: 40,
  streamDecay: 0.04,
  theta: 0.06
};

// Nodes
var nodes = [
  { id: 'hub',      label: 'Kieleth', r: 26, x: 400, y: 300, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'alpha',    label: 'Alpha',   r: 16, x: 500, y: 200, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'beta',     label: 'Beta',    r: 16, x: 300, y: 400, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'gamma',    label: 'Gamma',   r: 14, x: 250, y: 180, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'delta',    label: 'Delta',   r: 14, x: 550, y: 380, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'epsilon',  label: 'Epsilon', r: 12, x: 350, y: 150, vx: 0, vy: 0 }
];

// Spring edges connecting nodes
var edges = [
  { a: 'hub', b: 'alpha',   rest: 160, k: 0.006 },
  { a: 'hub', b: 'beta',    rest: 160, k: 0.005 },
  { a: 'hub', b: 'gamma',   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
  { a: 'hub', b: 'delta',   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
  { a: 'hub', b: 'epsilon', rest: 180, k: 0.003 },
  { a: 'alpha', b: 'beta',    rest: 200, k: 0.002 },
  { a: 'gamma', b: 'delta',   rest: 220, k: 0.002 },
  { a: 'alpha', b: 'epsilon', rest: 200, k: 0.002 }
];

// Camera state
var camera = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };
var cameraTarget = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };

// Particle stream
var particles = [];
var frameCount = 0;

// Find a node by its ID
function findNode(id) {
  for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    if (nodes[i].id === id) return nodes[i];
  }
  return null;
}

// Core physics simulation step
function simulatePhysics() {
  // 1) Repulsive forces between ALL node pairs (Coulomb-like / Lennard-Jones inspired)
  for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    for (var j = i + 1; j < nodes.length; j++) {
      var dx = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x;
      var dy = nodes[i].y - nodes[j].y;
      var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
      var force = config.attraction / (dist * dist);
      var fx = (dx / dist) * force;
      var fy = (dy / dist) * force;

      nodes[i].vx += fx;
      nodes[i].vy += fy;
      nodes[j].vx -= fx;
      nodes[j].vy -= fy;
    }
  }

  // 2) Spring forces along edges (Hooke's law)
  for (var e = 0; e < edges.length; e++) {
    var nodeA = findNode(edges[e].a);
    var nodeB = findNode(edges[e].b);
    if (!nodeA || !nodeB) continue;

    var dx = nodeB.x - nodeA.x;
    var dy = nodeB.y - nodeA.y;
    var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
    var displacement = dist - edges[e].rest;
    var force = (edges[e].k || config.frictionCoeff) * displacement;

    nodeA.vx += (dx / dist) * force;
    nodeA.vy += (dy / dist) * force;
    nodeB.vx -= (dx / dist) * force;
    nodeB.vy -= (dy / dist) * force;
  }

  // 3) Per-node: apply dispersal (centering gravity), damping, and integration
  for (var n = 0; n < nodes.length; n++) {
    // Dispersal force: pull toward center (400, 300)
    nodes[n].vx += (400 - nodes[n].x) * config.dispersal;
    nodes[n].vy += (300 - nodes[n].y) * config.dispersal;

    // Damping (amplification factor — velocity is scaled down each frame)
    nodes[n].vx *= config.amplification;
    nodes[n].vy *= config.amplification;

    // Euler integration: update position
    nodes[n].x += nodes[n].vx;
    nodes[n].y += nodes[n].vy;
  }
}

// Spawn a new decorative particle from a random node
function spawnParticle() {
  if (particles.length >= config.streamMax) return;

  var sourceNode = nodes[Math.floor(Math.random() * nodes.length)];
  var angle = Math.random() * TAU;
  var speed = 0.3 + Math.random() * SQRT_HALF;

  particles.push({
    x: sourceNode.x,
    y: sourceNode.y,
    vx: Math.cos(angle) * speed,
    vy: Math.sin(angle) * speed,
    age: 0,
    maxAge: 800 + Math.random() * 1200,
    size: 0.8 + (Math.random() * PHI) * SQRT_HALF
  });
}

// Update all particles (move, decay, remove dead ones)
function updateParticles() {
  for (var i = particles.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    var p = particles[i];

    // Age and remove expired particles
    p.age++;
    if (p.age > p.maxAge) {
      particles.splice(i, 1);
      continue;
    }

    // Apply drag/decay to velocity
    p.vx *= (1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125);
    p.vy *= (1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125);

    // Move
    p.x += p.vx;
    p.y += p.vy;
  }
}

// Smoothly interpolate camera toward its target
function updateCamera() {
  camera.x += (cameraTarget.x - camera.x) * config.theta;
  camera.y += (cameraTarget.y - camera.y) * config.theta;
  camera.zoom += (cameraTarget.zoom - camera.zoom) * config.theta;
}

// Main tick function, called every 16ms (~60fps)
function tick() {
  simulatePhysics();
  updateParticles();
  updateCamera();

  // Spawn a particle every 3rd frame
  if (frameCount % 3 === 0) spawnParticle();
  frameCount++;
}

setInterval(tick, 16);
```

---

## What It Does

This is the **physics engine** behind a force-directed graph visualization. Here's a breakdown of each system:

### 1. Force-Directed Graph Layout
A classic force-directed algorithm with two competing forces:
- **Repulsion** between every pair of nodes (inverse-square law: `attraction / dist²`) — pushes nodes apart, like charged particles
- **Spring attraction** along edges (Hooke's law: `force = k × displacement`) — pulls connected nodes toward a rest length

This naturally organizes connected nodes into a readable, organic layout.

### 2. Damping & Centering
- **Amplification (0.92)**: Each frame, velocities are multiplied by 0.92 — this is actually *damping* (not amplification). It bleeds kinetic energy so the system converges to equilibrium rather than oscillating forever
- **Dispersal (0.0003)**: A gentle centering gravity that pulls all nodes toward (400, 300), preventing the graph from drifting off-canvas

### 3. Particle System
Decorative particles are spawned from random nodes and drift outward:
- Up to 40 particles at once, spawned every 3rd frame
- Each has a random direction, speed, lifetime (800–2000 frames), and size
- Velocity decays over time via `streamDecay`
- Expired particles are removed

This creates a subtle ambient "energy streaming" visual effect around the graph.

### 4. Smooth Camera
The camera smoothly interpolates toward a target position/zoom using `theta (0.06)` as the lerp factor — a simple exponential ease-out.

---

## About the Misleading Blog Post

The author's blog post descriptions are **deliberately misleading**:

| Blog claim | Reality |
|---|---|
| "attraction" is attractive at short range | It's **repulsive** — `force / dist²` pushes nodes apart |
| "amplification" accelerates convergence | It's **damping** — multiplying by 0.92 removes energy each frame |
| "frictionCoeff" is spring friction/dissipation | It's actually the **spring constant** (stiffness `k`) fallback |
| "dispersal pushes isolated nodes toward edges" | It pulls nodes **toward the center**, not toward edges |
| "inertiaCore / inertiaNode" control rotational inertia | These parameters **don't exist** in the code at all |

The parameter names and descriptions appear intentionally inverted or fabricated — a fun obfuscation layer on top of the code obfuscation itself.
